land":"Northamptonshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Somerset, or Worcester, City of Worcester, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Worcestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1364–31 December 1438":"1364–31 December 1438","1350–1396":"1350–1396","1364–1438":"1364–1438","1365–1394":"1365–1394","1330–Female":"1330–Deceased","1385–1442":"1385–1442","1390–1448":"1390–1448","1340–1396":"1340–1396","1322–1384":"1322–1384","31 December 1438":"31 December 1438","1385":"1385","1396":"1396","1363":"1363","1330":"1330","1384":"1384","1340":"1340","1394":"1394","1350":"1350","before 20 October 1391":"before 20 October 1391","1390":"1390","1448":"1448","4 September 1394":"4 September 1394","1322":"1322","1442":"1442","1365":"1365","1364":"1364","March 1384":"March 1384","1438":"1438","Grafton, Yorkshire, England":"Grafton, Yorkshire, England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","Somerset, or Worcester, City of Worcester, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John Bedlisgate II was born in 1364, in Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Thomas John Bedlisgate, was 24 and his mother, Joan Beauchamp, was 42. He married Mary Beauchamp about 1357. He died on 31 December 1438, in his hometown, at the age of 74."},"et":{"1364–31 December 1438":"1364–31. detsember 1438","1350–1396":"1350–1396","1364–1438":"1364–1438","1365–1394":"1365–1394","1330–Female":"1330–Surnud","1385–1442":"1385–1442","1390–1448":"1390–1448","1340–1396":"1340–1396","1322–1384":"1322–1384","31 December 1438":"31. detsember 1438","1385":"1385","1396":"1396","1363":"1363","1330":"1330","1384":"1384","1340":"1340","1394":"1394","1350":"1350","before 20 October 1391":"enne 20. oktoobrit 1391","1390":"1390","1448":"1448","4 September 1394":"4. september 1394","1322":"1322","1442":"1442","1365":"1365","1364":"1364","March 1384":"märts 1384","1438":"1438","Grafton, Yorkshire, England":"Grafton, Yorkshire, England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Somerset, or Worcester, City of Worcester, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Worcestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1364–31 December 1438":"1364–31. joulukuuta 1438","1350–1396":"1350–1396","1364–1438":"1364–1438","1365–1394":"1365–1394","1330–Female":"1330–Kuollut","1385–1442":"1385–1442","1390–1448":"1390–1448","1340–1396":"